Thank you for your answers!   




 To conclude, we would like you to answer a few questions about your background and your experience in this survey. 




 How old are you?
clarity: How clear were the instructions in this survey?
comment: Do you have any other comments or suggestions?
The fact that a new participant can see what answers other participants had chosen before can change their own answer. I'm not sure if that's a good thing
I found the instructions very clear in this study - I am actually doing a dissertation myself at the moment so I found completing another piece of research really helpful.
None, thank you for the simple, and well laid out study!
Most students I know are adhering to the guidance. Only a few are not.

It might be worth capturing whether people have a disability. 
I am severally sight impaired and have almost no peripheral vision. 
This means I cannot move away in time to maintain the distance if the other person chooses to come close to me.
I think it should be clearer whether I need to answer entirely truthfully or answer in the way that would get the most bonus.

I am currently in isolation with housemates who have tested positive which sways my answers to this survey. May be worth asking this question - my answers would have been different if I was not in isolation.

It is a very fun way of completing a survey with easy to complete questions and good answering options. I would recommend showing the results of the most commonly clicked after I have clicked my results as seeing the results before could effect people's choices due to feelings of maybe guilt for being in a situation with a low percentage of people doing the same action.

I think there should be a qualifying question at the beginning to determine whether people have been self-isolating (voluntarily or mandatorily) over the preceding week, so as to ensure that the sample is representative of the general population. 
Otherwise, survey was clear and concise - which is much appreciated.
I didn't quite understand whether I was supposed to be telling the truth so I did but it was a bit unclear if the aim was to maximise gains or tell the truth
Thanks! Hope I get more surveys like this :)
The survey was clear from the beginning unlike a lot of other student based surveys I have participated in whereby the survey's instructions were too long and not as concise/to the point.
The survey was very short and concise which made it extremely easy to answer the questions.
The question about indoor activity, as my full time job is a teacher, my answer was yes - but it was with social distancing and so on.

More specific on indoor socialising question as could be misconstrued as myself breaking the rules. I am a student on placement who has ticked yes for these but not breaking any rules as it is for work.
Have been avoiding people were i can, and when out and about.
I'm in college. I have no choice but to be inside with my "bubble" with no social distancing.
Good survey, simple and concise. Liked it a lot
It’s not entirely clear whether the “6 people who are not from my household” are ALL not from my household or SOME not from my household
I didn't understand the bonus system. I just answered truthfully
The question for the interaction with someone who's experiencing a symptom of Covid-19 didn't state if it's a physical interaction or remote interaction. I think this addition will be better.
It would be good to have the percentages revealed after answering rather than before.
Having the answers form last week and the optional bonus for correct answers may make people biased.
Nope I found the survey quite good.
Great survey. Nice to know the scores of other participants.

It's strange to me that you offered bonus as an incentive for us to pick what others did.. Would this not make people pick the more frequent answer just to get the bonus payment and then not give you true data?
For me, I answered by my experience but in some cases when I wasn't sure I was more drawn to pick a more frequent answer.
As I am from Wales we are currently in lockdown so we can not go out in social gatherings at all.

Some of the questions (ie the one about being in a lift/elevator with someone else) didn't specify whether or not it mattered if the other person was a member of one's household/bubble, which seems relevant.
i AM DOMICILED IN wALES AND some of your questioned referred to English restrictions that are different to ours
education level should show UK version. Im in first year at uni

Include A levels as an option for education level
Add questions with extended time range
No, everything in this survey went perfectly well.
